Given a newly discovered fossil specimen of *Calanticidae* exhibiting anomalous biomineralization patterns in its exoskeletal microstructure, and assuming that the organism lived during the Late Cretaceous in a low-oxygen, high-sulfide marine environment, determine the thermodynamic feasibility of the proposed metabolic pathway involving sulfur-reducing archaea symbionts that co-evolved with the host. Specifically, derive the net Gibbs free energy change ($\Delta G^\circ_{\text{net}}$) for the coupled reaction sequence:  
$$
\text{C}_6\text{H}_{12}\text{O}_6 + 2\text{SO}_4^{2-} \rightarrow 2\text{CO}_2 + 2\text{HS}^- + 2\text{H}^+ + 2\text{H}_2\text{O}
$$
under the following constraints:  
- The standard reduction potentials are $E^\circ(\text{SO}_4^{2-}/\text{HS}^-) = -0.22\ \text{V}$ and $E^\circ(\text{CO}_2/\text{C}_6\text{H}_{12}\text{O}_6) = -0.43\ \text{V}$;  
- The intracellular pH is 6.8, and the ambient pH is 7.4;  
- The concentrations are $[\text{C}_6\text{H}_{12}\text{O}_6] = 1.5\ \mu\text{M}$, $[\text{SO}_4^{2-}] = 12\ \text{mM}$, $[\text{CO}_2] = 0.3\ \text{mM}$, $[\text{HS}^-] = 8\ \mu\text{M}$, and $[\text{H}^+] = 10^{-6.8}\ \text{M}$;  
- The activity coefficients are assumed to be unity;  
- The reaction proceeds via two coupled half-reactions, with the electron transfer stoichiometry determined by the redox balance of the carbon and sulfur species.  

Additionally, evaluate whether this pathway could have supported the observed biomineralization rates (measured via synchrotron X-ray tomography as $1.2\ \mu\text{m}^3\ \text{per hour}$) in the fossilized exoskeleton, given that the mineral phase is identified as calcium sulfate (anhydrite) and the metabolic energy yield must account for both biosynthesis and passive precipitation. Provide a detailed derivation of the thermodynamic and kinetic constraints, and justify whether this system represents a viable evolutionary adaptation under the paleoenvironmental stressors of the time.

