**Conclusion** – The time‑dependent systemic vascular resistance under a constant nitroglycerin infusion is

\[
\boxed{
\text{SVR}(t)=
\frac{\displaystyle \text{SVR}_{0}}
     {\displaystyle 1+\left[
        \frac{ V_{\max}\,
               \displaystyle\frac{\alpha\,C_{NG}}
               {(C_{NG}+K_{d})K_{m}+\alpha\,C_{NG}} }
             { k_{\text{inh}}\,[\text{PDE5}]\,IC_{50} }
        \Bigl(1-e^{-k_{\text{inh}}[\text{PDE5}]\,t}\Bigr)
        \right]^{\,n}}
}
\]

where  

* \(C_{NG}=R_{\text{inf}}/Cl\) (steady plasma nitroglycerin concentration; any equivalent expression linking the constant infusion rate \(R_{\text{inf}}\) to concentration may be used),  
* \(\alpha\) is the proportionality constant relating the fraction of ALDH2 occupied by nitroglycerin to the generated NO concentration,  
* \(K_{d}=k_{\text{off}}/k_{\text{on}}\) is the dissociation constant for the nitroglycerin‑ALDH2 complex,  
* \(V_{\max}\) and \(K_{m}\) are the maximal rate and Michaelis constant for sGC activation by NO,  
* \(k_{\text{inh}}\,[\text{PDE5}]\equiv k_{\text{deg}}\) is the effective first‑order rate constant for PDE5‑mediated cGMP degradation,  
* \(IC_{50}\) is the cGMP concentration producing half‑maximal reduction in SVR, and  
* \(n\) is the Hill coefficient describing the steepness of the SVR‑cGMP relationship.  

The expression assumes rapid‑equilibrium binding of nitroglycerin to ALDH2, constant NO production proportional to the bound fraction, Michaelis–Menten sGC activation, linear PDE5‑mediated cGMP clearance, and a Hill‑type inverse relation between cGMP and vascular resistance.

